posts.title: Did Donald Trump Lose The 2020 Election? Statistic models show the chances are less than 0.02%
posts.content:
Let's talk about the fact that no incumbent president in a 150 years has gained votes in a reelection campaign and still lost. Trump gained 10 million votes from his 2016 victory. To win, Biden had to shatter Barack Obama's popular vote totals while consistently trailing Trump in measures of voter enthusiasm. ‌ Let's talk about the fact that Biden was the first president in 60 years to lose Ohio, lose Florida, and still win the election. And he didn't just lose. Polls said he was gonna win, and he lost Ohio by 8 points and Florida by more than 3. ‌ The last time this happened, JFK's father allegedly used the mafia of dead people vote in Illinois to beat Nixon. ‌ Even more interestingly, there are 19 bellwether counties that have predicted every election in the past 40 years. 18 of 19 voted for Trump by an average of 16 points. If you expand that further, there are 58 bellwether counties that have correctly predicted every president since 2000, and Trump won 51 of them by an average of 15 points. ‌ Or we can look at the fact that there were 27 toss-up congressional districts and the Republicans won all 27, yet Biden won the presidency.

While we're at it, we can talk about the primary votes that have been remarkably accurate in predicting general election winners. ‌ In fact, no incumbent president who has received 75% of the total primary vote has lost reelection. Trump received 94% of the primary vote, which is the 4th highest of all time higher than Eisenhower, Nixon, Clinton, or Obama. ‌ In fact, Trump is only one of 5 incumbent since 1912 to receive more than 90% of the primary vote. Trump set a record for the most primary votes received by an incumbent when more than 18,000,000 people turned out for him in 2020. ‌ Previous number held by Bill Clinton was less than half that number. For Biden to prevail in the general election, despite Trump's historic support in the primaries, turns a century's work of prior election data on its head. ‌ So I'm asking you to ignore all of these statistical anomalies, (see video graph) and the fact that Biden got middle of the night votes at extraordinarily improbable rates. ‌
